The course gives an overview of the most important quantitative and qualitative research methods in philology (linguistics, applied linguistics, study of literature and culture), as well as their advantages and disadvantages. The course prepares doctoral candidates for conducting and presenting independent research. Seminars are dedicated to the discussion of methods used by students and problems that have arisen in the course of work.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course gives an overview of the most important quantitative and qualitative research methods in philology (linguistics, applied linguistics, study of literature and culture). The course prepares doctoral candidates for conducting and presenting independent research. Seminars are dedicated to the discussion of methods used by students and problems that have arisen in the course of work.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Students have in-depth understanding of different quantitative and qualitative research methods used in philological research. They are ready to plan and conduct independent research and present their findings. Students improve their skill of logical systematic thinking necessary for conducting valid and reliable research (both academic and practical) and presenting it in a coherent fashion.
